Why do we need volumes in Kubernetes?

 Pods are ephemeral. If a Pod is deleted or recreated, data stored inside the Pod is lost. Volumes provide storage that applications can use to preserve or share data.

WWhich applications require persistent storage?

Examples:

MySQL
PostgreSQL
MongoDB
Elasticsearch
Jenkins
Prometheus
Grafana (for dashboards if configured to persist)
Applications that store user-uploaded files

Types of Kubernetes Volumes

├── emptyDir/simple mount
├── hostPath
├── ConfigMap
├── Secret
├── Persistent Volume (PV)
├── Persistent Volume Claim (PVC)
├── StorageClass
├── AWS EBS
├── AWS EFS
├── Azure Disk
├── GCE Persistent Disk
└── NFS

1.Empty Dir:

this is depandent on pod lifecycle, that is when pod is created ,volume gets created and when you delet the pod the volume and the content inside it aslo get deleted , 

syntex :
create the pod with volume and voulume mount 


apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: empty-directory
  namespace: default

spec:
  containers:
    - name: nginx
      image: nginx
      ports:
        - containerPort: 80
      volumeMounts:
        - name: empty-directory-volume
          mountPath: /data

  volumes:
    - name: empty-directory-volume
      emptyDir: {}

run command ;

kubectl apply -f <file name>   # it will cret the pod
kubectl exec -it <pod name> -- sh  # enter into the pod and go inside the path "/data" and crete some file (test.txt)  and list the file, it exists ,


now run:
kubectl delete pod <pod name>   # it will delete the pod
lubectl exec -it <pod name> -- sh #now check the path /data, now list the file (test.txt)  which is ceted before the deletion of the pod, the file will not be present, 


so it is clear that the data is lost when ever the pod is deleted .


that is how the emptdir works 

